:::summary
Thucydides (c. 460–400 BC) was the Athenian historian and general whose account of the Peloponnesian War — the great conflict between Athens and Sparta — established the foundations of modern historical writing. His insistence on eyewitness evidence, his analysis of human nature and political power, and his unflinching realism make him not only the father of scientific history but one of the most penetrating thinkers of antiquity.
:::

